{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"531d141e-3d8a-41cf-9ca7-031b90975468","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the `webapi` template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n**Authentication options** (`--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|--------|-------------|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Example with auth:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need custom identity provider support (e.g., Auth0, Keycloak).\n\nWould you like help scaffolding a specific configuration?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7ad20c26-a64c-4f8f-800b-44cd866ffab3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":291,"requestId":"93C7:1ED665:A48D25:BDFE5D:69F2A7BD"},"id":"7cafe8a8-49b8-4ff8-bfd0-480431c83a74","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:52:21.232Z","parentId":"ec3b2590-9795-4c16-9919-cd6566a94b9d"}
